[thinking] **Evaluating Java class structure**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I’m exploring whether we can use static nested Java classes in our tests. The test appears to indicate that top-level class names can’t have a dollar sign ($), yet application classes can be nested. It seems dynamic loading class names might be causing issues, so I’m considering avoiding inner classes. I know that public classes with the main method should be in separate files, but I wonder if adding helper classes under src/test/java is permitted.
[thinking] 
[thinking] **Considering Java testing structure**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I'm thinking about how to set up a Java test file. It seems that while I can have public top-level test classes, non-public helper classes can go in the same file. But then, accessibility issues might crop up if I use package-private classes — reflection might not work correctly if the method isn’t public or if it’s being called from a different package. It’s probably best to keep the helper classes public. Using nested classes might help, but also brings some naming concerns.
[thinking] 
[thinking] **Examining test class structure**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I'm figuring out the setup for my test class file, which only has LauncherTest.java. It seems like native image reflection might require me to use nested classes, but there's a naming rule that says not to include a dollar sign ($) in test class names, which is confusing. 
[thinking] 
[thinking] I could create public helper classes nested within LauncherTest, ensuring the main method is designated as public static. From what I see, I can use reflection on these public nested classes effectively. Configuring runtime resources without hard-coding is a bit tricky, but it might be feasible by writing resource files dynamically.
[thinking] 
[thinking] **Considering custom ClassLoader**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I'm thinking about creating a custom ClassLoader that can return a ByteArrayInputStream for resource names, which might eliminate the need for test resources. This way, I could directly call mainWithExitCode, covering the getResourceAsStream functionality. 
[thinking] 
[thinking] I want to make sure that the dynamic class loading is properly supported, particularly for loading test nested app classes. Using ClassWorld to create a new realm with a context loader seems like the right approach, so I'll investigate how DefaultClassRealm loads classes based on the classloader passed.
[thinking] 
